The paper deals with algorithms for computing edit distance, which is a fundamental problem in computer science and has applications in various fields such as natural language processing, bioinformatics, and data mining. The paper focuses on sublinear-time algorithms for small edit distance, which is a well-studied problem in theoretical computer science. The paper uses techniques from dynamic programming, sampling, and adaptive algorithms. Therefore, the most likely arXiv CS sub-categories are cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.CC (Computational Complexity), and cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also uses techniques from machine learning and statistics, which makes cs.LG (Machine Learning) a likely sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with combinatorial problems, which makes cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) a possible sub-category.
